<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,725,863]" box="[189,310,725,751]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,725,751]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,725,751]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,725,863]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Female inner spermathecae consist of one lateral extending sac and a divided round sac medially, on each side, with a small sclerotized reduced outer spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[926,994,803,830]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="7.[189,241,1965,1991]" captionTargetBox="[189,1310,703,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,703,1926]" captionText="Figs 1–8. Female internal genitalia. 1. Hexophthalma binfordae sp. nov. 2–4. H. goanikontesensis sp. nov. 5. H. leroyi sp. nov. 6–8. H. albospinosa (Purcell, 1908). Scale bar =1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1255330/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) which is unlike that of any of the other species. Male unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
